import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.dates as mdates

#When this code is run the first time, it gets the dates wrong. Please re-run to get the correct image

# Aggregate sales by category and date
category_sales = df.groupby(['CATEGORY', 'WEEK_END_DATE'])['UNITS'].sum().reset_index()

# Plot sales trends
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
sns.lineplot(data=category_sales, x='WEEK_END_DATE', y='UNITS', hue='CATEGORY')
plt.title('Sales Trends by Category')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Units Sold')
plt.legend(title='Category')

# Format the x-axis to display month and year
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.MonthLocator())  # Locate months
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%b-%Y'))  # Format as Month-Year

plt.xticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate labels if needed for better readability
plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to make room for the rotated x-axis labels

plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd

categories = ['BAG SNACKS', 'COLD CEREAL', 'FROZEN PIZZA', 'ORAL HYGIENE PRODUCTS']


# Creating a figure to hold the subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 1, figsize=(14, 21))

# List of promotion types for iteration
promotion_types = ['FEATURE', 'DISPLAY', 'TPR_ONLY']

# Iterate through each type of promotion to create separate plots
for i, promo in enumerate(promotion_types):
    # Group by category and the promotion type, then calculate mean units sold
    promo_impact = df.groupby(['CATEGORY', promo])['UNITS'].mean().reset_index()
    
    # Create a barplot for each promotion type
    barplot = sns.barplot(data=promo_impact, x='CATEGORY', y='UNITS', hue=promo, ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_title(f'Impact of {promo} Promotion on Sales by Category')
    axes[i].set_xlabel('Category')
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Average Units Sold')
    axes[i].legend(title=promo)

    # Adding the text labels on the bars
    for bar in barplot.patches:
        barplot.annotate(format(bar.get_height(), '.1f'), 
                         (bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, 
                          bar.get_height()), ha='center', va='center',
                          size=15, xytext=(0, 8),
                          textcoords='offset points')

# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In [14]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.dates as mdates


df['WEEK_END_DATE'] = pd.to_datetime(df['WEEK_END_DATE'])
df['Month_Year'] = df['WEEK_END_DATE'].dt.to_period('M').dt.to_timestamp()

promotion_types = ['FEATURE', 'DISPLAY', 'TPR_ONLY']
categories = df['CATEGORY'].unique()

# Creating subplots for each category and promotion type
fig, axes = plt.subplots(len(categories) * len(promotion_types), 1, figsize=(14, 6 * len(categories) * len(promotion_types)))

for i, category in enumerate(categories):
    for j, promo in enumerate(promotion_types):
        # Filter data for the current category and where the promotion is active
        filtered_data = df[(df['CATEGORY'] == category) & (df[promo] == 1)]
        
        # Group by 'Month_Year' and count occurrences of the promotion
        promo_usage = filtered_data.groupby('Month_Year').size().reset_index(name='Counts')
        
        # Calculate the subplot index (0-based)
        subplot_index = i * len(promotion_types) + j
        ax = axes[subplot_index]
        
        # Plot
        sns.lineplot(data=promo_usage, x='Month_Year', y='Counts', ax=ax, marker='o')
        ax.set_title(f'Usage of {promo} Promotion in {category} Over Time')
        ax.set_xlabel('Month and Year')
        ax.set_ylabel('Promotion Count')

        # Formatting x-axis
        ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.MonthLocator())
        ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%b-%Y'))
        ax.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.dates as mdates

# Aggregate the data to calculate average sales for each month within each category, but keep 'WEEK_END_DATE' for plotting
monthly_sales = df.groupby(['CATEGORY', pd.Grouper(key='WEEK_END_DATE', freq='M')])['UNITS'].mean().reset_index()

# Plot seasonal trends across categories
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
sns.lineplot(data=monthly_sales, x='WEEK_END_DATE', y='UNITS', hue='CATEGORY')
plt.title('Seasonal Sales Trends by Category')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Average Units Sold')
plt.legend(title='Category')

# Format the x-axis to display months and years
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.MonthLocator())  # Locate months
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%b-%Y'))  # Format as Month-Year

plt.xticks(rotation=45) 
plt.tight_layout() 

plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

numerical_data = df[['UNITS', 'PRICE', 'FEATURE', 'DISPLAY', 'TPR_ONLY']].copy()

# Convert boolean promotional flags to numeric if they aren't already
numerical_data['FEATURE'] = numerical_data['FEATURE'].astype(int)
numerical_data['DISPLAY'] = numerical_data['DISPLAY'].astype(int)
numerical_data['TPR_ONLY'] = numerical_data['TPR_ONLY'].astype(int)

# Calculate the correlation matrix
corr_matrix = numerical_data.corr()

# Plot the correlation matrix using a heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='.2f')
plt.title('Correlation Matrix of Sales, Price, and Promotions')
plt.show()
